1.Understand the Parameter:
  The Exponential Distribution has a rate parameter λ (lambda) which represents the rate of occurrence.
  The probability density function (PDF) is:
  f(x)=λ⋅e^(−λx),x≥0
2. Set Up Excel Table:
  Column A: Values of x from 0 to, say, 10 (interval of 0.5 or 1).
  Column B: Use the EXPON.DIST function in Excel:
  =EXPON.DIST(x, λ, FALSE)
  For cumulative probabilities, use TRUE instead of FALSE.
3. Plot the Graph:
  Use a line chart for continuous distribution:
  X-axis: Time or event spacing (x)
  Y-axis: Probability density f(x)
  Title: “Exponential Distribution (λ = …)”
  Label axes: Time (x) and Probability Density f(x)
